        min_cost_first_type = -1
        min_cost_second_type = -1

        for cost in [cost_first_type, cost_second_type]:
            cost_to_buy = min(n_i, cost)
            if cost_to_buy > 0:
                min_cost = min(min_cost, cost_to_buy)
                if cost_first_type == cost:
                    min_cost_first_type = min(min_cost_first_type, cost_to_buy)
                if cost_second_type == cost:
                    min_cost_second_type = min(min_cost_second_type, cost_to_buy)

        min_cost = min(min_cost, min(n_i - min(min_cost_first_type, min_cost_second_type), n_i))
        
        print(min_cost)

Solution:

We can solve this problem using dynamic programming. We will use a 2D array `visited` to keep track of the points that we have visited. We will initialize the `visited` array with all points as initially unvisited. We will then fill in the `visited` array as we traverse the key points.

We will start by initializing the `visited` array with all points as unvisited. Then, for each level of the key points, we will create a 2D array of size `n x n` where `n` is the number of levels. We will fill in this 2D array with all `True` values initially, indicating that we have visited all the points of the corresponding level.

Finally, we will iterate through all the levels of the key points from the minimum level to the maximum level, and for each level, we will iterate through all the points in that level. For each point, we will check if we have already visited that point in the current level. If we have not visited that point, we will mark it as visited in the current level and move to the next level.

We will keep track of the minimum possible total distance Maksim has to travel by iterating through all the points of the given levels. We will calculate the total distance by summing up all the distances of all the points in the current level.

Solution:
We can solve this problem in O(k) extra space using a two-dimensional array. We will use the row index k to represent the elements in the row. We will iterate over the array from the second element down to the third element, and for each element we will use a two-dimensional array to store the sums of the elements directly above it.

We will initialize the first element of the first row with 1, and the second element of the first row with the value at the first index. We will then iterate over the array starting from the third element and work our way down to the second-to-last element, using the first two elements to get the sum of the elements above it.

Solution:
We can solve this problem by using dynamic programming. We will store the minimum time required for each team to complete one algorithm in a list. We will also keep track of the minimum time required by each team for each algorithm.

Let's start with the base case: If we have no teams, or if we have only one team, we can return the same minimum time as the given time.

Then, we can use dynamic programming to solve the problem. We will initialize the first row with a fixed value of 0. We will then fill in the rest of the rows with the minimum time required for each team to complete one algorithm.

For each team, we will update the minimum time required by each algorithm to be the minimum of the minimum time required by each algorithm for the previous team and the minimum time required for the team to complete the algorithm in that algorithm. We will also update the minimum time required by each algorithm for the current team to be the minimum of the minimum time required by each algorithm for the previous team and the minimum time required for the current team to complete the algorithm in that algorithm.

Finally, we will return the minimum value among the rows.
